03976nam a22005055i 9780773560741DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19781978xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807735607417 a10.1515/97807735607412doi  a(DE-B1597)657818  a(OCoLC)1394871978  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aLE3.Q32 ǂb Q43 1978eb 7aHIS0000002bisacsh04a378.713/721 aNeatby, Hilda, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aQueen's University :bVolume I, 1841-1917: And Not to Yield /cHilda Neatby. 1aMontreal ;aKingston ;aLondon ;aChicago : bMcGill-Queen's University Press, c[1978] 4c©1978  a1 online resource (363 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tIllustrations -- tForeword -- tPreface -- t"A Token for Good" -- tThe Founding of Queen's -- t"Deep Humiliation" -- tThe Bible College -- tRoots and Branches -- tThe Trials of Principal Leitch -- tSevere Shocks and a Fresh Start -- t"A Marvellous Vitality" -- tPrincipal Grant -- tLearning on a Little Oatmeal -- tA Unique Freedom -- tFaculties New and Old -- tQueen's and a National Ideal -- tConstitutional Controversy -- tA National University -- tQueen's and World War I -- tNotes -- tBibliography -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThe figure of Grant inevitably dominates this volume, but full recognition is given to other builders and preservers of Queen's, notably William Snodgrass, the pilot who weathered the storms of the Sixties and Seventies, and Daniel Miner Gordon, who presided over the secularization of the university in the early years of this century. Outstanding scholars, teachers, and administrators such as Watson, Williamson, MacKerras, Macnaughton, Dupuis, Shortt, Cappon, Goodwin, and Chown also figure prominently. The author examines in detail the role of the Board of Trustees, the Senate, and the undergraduate Alma Mater Society in the development of Queen's, and explores the complex relationships with the Presbyterian Church, the sister institutions in Toronto, and the provincial government. She shows how the distinctive character of Queen's was shaped by the Scottish heritage, evident in an emphasis upon flexible curricula, close faculty-student relations, and the virtues of student self-government, as well as in a sturdy independence in the face of repeated pressure for the concentration of higher education in Ontario. Imbued with a warm appreciation of the traditions of Queen's University and a scholar's critical detachement, this book is an important contribution to the history of institutional growth in Canada.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / General.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010z978311127416408iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010z978311127724040uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/978077356074140uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780773560741423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/document/cover/isbn/9780773560741/original  a978-3-11-127416-4  ACUP Complete eBook-Package Pre-2010b2010  a978-3-11-127724-0  ACUP Upgrade eBook-Package pre 2010b2010  aGBV-deGruyter-alles